<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-231-832  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 231 832.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  April 24 1989 v10 n17 p20(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Automation: where will you be when the lights go out? (unattendedcomputer operations) (part two in three-part series on networkmanagement myths)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Duckworth, Vicki.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>In order for the dream of a fully automated, lights-out computerroom environment to be achieved, operating systems, subsystems andapplications must be included in network management.andP;  Systems andnetwork architectures today are becoming too large and complex forany human being to handle.andP;  But full processor automation in thecontext of multi-processor sites and multi-site enterprises adds alevel of complexity requiring flexible automation tools.andP;  A commondata repository for network and system management data and theability to display information are important initial steps.andO;Operators must also be able to establish and modify automationrules without having to deal with procedural language coding.andP;  Anarchitecture must be developed that provides a set of toolsincluding a repository, a flexible language and a rule-basedautomation capability.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Network ManagementManagement of EDPData ManagementProcessor ArchitectureControl SystemsFully Automated.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>